To a layman, this solve path means:

**“We are shopping for the best spring, not just checking whether one spring can survive.”**

That is the big difference.

This is not the fatigue path where you analyze one finished design.
This is a **selection** path.

You give the app a list of candidate wire sizes, and it does two things:

First, it throws out the candidates that are physically bad ideas using a set of go/no-go checks. In your app, those checks include active-coil count, spring-index range, buckling, solid-height limit, free-length limit, and optionally frequency margin. A candidate is only called feasible if it passes all of them. Then, among the feasible ones, the app chooses the one with the best figure of merit.

Second, it ranks the survivors using a figure of merit. In your code, that figure of merit is based on relative cost and spring size, through
(-(\text{relative cost}) \pi^2 d^2 N_t D / 4). That means the app is favoring designs that do the job with less material and lower relative cost, not just designs that barely survive.

So to a layman, the result is not:

* “Can this spring exist?”

It is:

* **“Which of these possible springs is the smartest practical choice?”**

## What the results mean physically

Each candidate spring is a different tradeoff between:

* wire thickness,
* coil diameter,
* number of coils,
* free length,
* stiffness,
* and stability.

The go/no-go inequalities are the app’s way of saying:

* too many coils? too floppy or too long
* too large or too small spring index? bad geometry or poor manufacturability
* buckles? physically unstable
* too tall free length or too big solid height? it will not fit
* fails frequency check? may vibrate badly in service

So when a candidate is crossed out, that is not abstract math. It means:

**“This spring may look okay on paper, but in the real world it would be awkward, unstable, too large, or otherwise a bad design.”**

Then the figure of merit answers:

**“Among the candidates that are not stupid, which one is the most efficient choice?”**

## Is the spring a good spring?

In this solve path, a “good spring” means:

* it carries the required load,
* stays elastic,
* fits the packaging,
* does not buckle,
* stays in a practical geometry range,
* and is a better overall compromise than the other feasible candidates.

So yes, if a spring ends up as the selected design, the app is saying:

**“This is not just acceptable. This is the best acceptable option among the candidates you tested.”**

That is more meaningful than a simple pass/fail.

## Why the figure of merit matters

Without the figure of merit, you could easily end up with several springs that all technically work.

Then what?

You still need a way to choose.

The figure of merit is basically a **tie-breaker with engineering taste built in**:

* smaller,
* cheaper,
* less material,
* still functional.

So physically, it helps prevent overbuilt nonsense.

A spring that is twice as bulky as necessary might still work, but that does not make it a smart design.

This is why the solve path is valuable:
it does not stop at “works.”
It asks:
**“Which working spring deserves to win?”**

## What is the relevancy of these results?

The results tell you:

* which candidates are dead on arrival,
* why they fail,
* and which surviving design is the most efficient compromise.

That is extremely relevant in real engineering because most design work is not about finding *a* solution.
It is about finding a **good** solution under constraints.

So this solve path is really about **decision-making**.

If you had to explain it to a non-engineer:

**“The computer is screening a bunch of spring options, throwing out the bad ones, and then picking the most sensible one among the survivors.”**

That is the physical meaning.

## Are the designers engineering geniuses?

Usually not. Usually they are being disciplined and selective.

This kind of spring selection is less about genius and more about knowing that:

* many candidates can look plausible,
* some fail for boring practical reasons,
* and one of the survivors is usually the most economical and balanced choice.

The intelligence is in the filtering and the judgment.

That is what your app now reproduces:

* reject the bad candidates,
* compare the acceptable ones,
* pick the smartest compromise.

